data.message: Hello TSP members! Many thanks to those of you who have done our second follow-up survey sent out two weeks ago. For those of you who haven't, don't forget to check your email and complete it for a $20 gift card! You’ll earn an additional $20 at the end if you fill out all surveys!

Hello TSP members! Keep an eye out for the second follow-up survey that we’re sending out TODAY! Check your inbox and complete the survey to earn $20. Don’t forget that if you complete all of our follow-up surveys, you will receive an additional $20 at the end!

Hello TSP members! That last post concludes our 90-day program. Please check your email today for our first follow-up survey. You will receive a $20 gift card upon completion.We hope that our Facebook group has been enjoyable, educational, and life-changing in some way, whether it be a shift in your perspective towards smoking, or a commitment towards a healthier, smoke-free life. All of us at TSP have enjoyed reading your comments and interacting with you online, and we truly thank you for your participation.Although we will no longer be posting daily, you are welcome to remain in this secret group and access all of the content we've shared over the past 90 days. Furthermore, we're still available to answer any questions/concerns about smoking, and we're open to any feedback/suggestions you may have for our program. Again, from all of us at TSP, thank you and good luck in your future endeavors!

Quitting smoking is difficult  for the person who is psychologically addicted.A high score in Habit suggests that you no longer getting much satisfaction from cigarettes.

Baby steps are required to conquer smoking once and for all. Pick one of these small-steps to try and post your choice #freeyourself :• Quit smoking for 24 hours• Smoke five fewer cigarettes each day• Delay your first cigarette of the day by 10 minutes• Limit your smoking to one or two places only

In a survey of 800 New Yorkers:• 81 percent agreed that most people would not hire a smoker to take care of their children• 72 percent agreed that most non-smokers would be reluctant to date a smoker• 39 percent agreed that most people think less of a person who smokes• 21 percent agreed that most people think smoking is a sign of personal failure. What do YOU really think of smokers when you see them on the street? #knowyourself
Quitting smoking may not be number one on your current priorities list. What would make quitting more important to you? #TDII
That's it for today guys. Here are some more tips on exercise and quitting smoking:

Some people start out too fast or exercise too much and burn out after thinking about keeping up a regular exercise routine if they don’t already exercise regularly. Keep these things in mind:1. Start Gradually2. Set limited goals. For example:Week 1 = exercise 10 minutes every other day.Week 2 = add 5 minutes to your exercise time.Week 3 = add another 5 minutes to your exercise time.3.  Give yourself a one-month trial period.During the first few weeks, you should expect some initial discomfort while you gain strength and endurance. 4.  Be aware that achieving a high level of fitness after being out of shape takes about 3 to 4 months.
If you wanted to get info about how to quit smoking, where would you go? How would youknow the source was true? #beingconscious

Studies of former smokers show that it is extremely helpful to know where, when, and why you are most likely to smoke. data.message: Remember Drawback #1 ("I don't want to have withdrawal symptoms") from yesterday’s post? Which one of our following comebacks would work for you? #balance• I can tell myself that some withdrawal symptoms are actually signs that my body is healing• I can tell myself that I may be coughing more because the cilia (hair-like structures that line my lungs and clean the air I breathe) that were paralyzed by the cigarette smoke are starting to work again, which makes me temporaril y cough more• I can tell myself I may have tingling in my arms and legs because my circulation is improving
The healing comeback, it's nice to feel my body fixing itself from all the damage.
Probably the First One , And Also Stating All The Things That Are Improving With Not smoking

Everyone wants to know whether electronic cigarettes can help smokers quit. Unfortunately studies are showing that they are not any more effective than a placebo. So health professionals still recommend using well-studies strategies like counseling or nicotine replacement therapy (patch, gum) when you’re ready to quit. #ecig
I think seeking other help besides the e-cigs is wise. I tried to do just the e-cig and of course failed.
Many e-cig companies are actually owned by BIG TOBACCO companies. What do you think their motives are? Remain a loyal customer? Help you quit smoking? Other ideas? #ecig
To further their business and monopolize the business.
To give people a "healthier" option without losing business.
What would be the best-case scenario if you quit smoking? #balance
I would lose dependency on an item when I'm stressed or hurt and could actually face what was causing those feelings right away. And I would save so much money.
Best case scenario is having a stable support and never going back to it.

Avoiding weight gain is on the top of the list of concerns for almost every smoker. We get it and have made a list of some tips that can help keep your weight on track while you quit. Pick which one sounds best to you. How could you implement it into your life? #balance • Go for a walk, swim, bike ride or any exercise you enjoy• Find small ways to be more active like taking the stairs instead of the elevator or parking a little further away• Find alternatives to snacking like calling a friend• Drink some extra water
I'd go for the walking option and would just find ways like when I go to the store or mabey work if possible walk, and reward myself with something for reaching a walking goal after a week.
Walking is a good option, I love being outdoors.

Here are some things to help you maintain your physique when you stop smoking. Read them over and tell us what sounds like it would help you the most. #balance • Make sure you have a well-balanced diet• Chew sugarless gum when you want something sweet• Eat slowly• Plan healthy, low-fat and low-calorie snacks into your day• Watch portion sizes• Read food labels

I personally find that in taking the given amounts isn't as healthy for me personally , and something that would help me is portion size because a lot of times I eat beyond my amount of hunger specially in times of stress.
Planning would help me the most. I'm horrible with sticking to something without a plan.

Research shows making the benefits of quitting more important than the drawbacks helps smokers quit their habit for good. So try your hand at making a negative a positive and tell us, what's your comeback for this drawback? #balance
The withdrawal symptoms only LAST a little while, the benefits of quitting LAST a lifetime

Here are some options that can help you deal with cigarette cravings that may come up during the holidays (these tips can be useful to check out even if you don’t want to quit right now or just want to reduce). Happy Holidays everyone! http://www.mayoclinic.org/healthy-living/quit-smoking/in-depth/nicotine-craving/art-20045454

For any of you that aren’t sure what an e-cig is, take a look at this FDA page explaining what they are and some of the controversy surrounding their regulations. Do any of you feel that if you were a minor, an e-cig would be more appealing and seem “safer” to try than a traditional cigarette? #beingconscious
They might appeal as more safe but they are also more expensive short term if I were a minor I would probably still choose a tradition cigarette

data.caption: The Doctor Is In
data.description: Hi everyone and welcome to the group. Tomorrow, I will be holding the first "The Doctor Is In" session. You can ask me everything you want to know around smoking, quitting, and the Tobacco Status Project. See you then!

data.message: Share a success that you have had in the past. It can be anything from any time. Why did it work? Who helped? #motivation
I quit for my entire pregnancy, but then I even quit for 2 more months after that.. I had my family trying to quit as well, but then I got really stressed out with money and I went back at it.
I dont know if it has to be about smoking, but i jus finished my first term of college with good grades, and i only made it through with help from my family, and because i wasnt afraid to get help.
How would you support someone who tells you they want to quit smoking? #motivation
Try not to smoke around them & be there for them if they ever feel weak. Also not be judgemental if they should fail.
support them with what they need, and let them figure out at what pace and how they wanna quit.
Educate yourself on the smoking rates and laws in your state. Check out the “Smoking Information” and “Smoking bans” in your state. Did any of the information surprise you? #smokingaffectsall
I actually thought it was banned from smoking indoors sooner than 1995.
But I don't like being told I can't smoke outside..
I was just surprised by how much higher my state is in underage smoking compared to other states.
